A fourth is indecency, not only degrading to a public speaker, but hardly sufferable at a gentlemen's dinner- -.party When all these modes, then, are withheld from this branch of oratory, the residue of wit depends apparently either on the facts or on the language, in accordance with the distinction I have already drawn. For the joke which still remains witty, in whatever words it is couched, has its germ in the facts; that which loses its pungency, as soon as it is differently worded, owes all its humour to the lang-uage.
